# HTMX Cursor Rules

## Architecture
- Return HTML fragments from server, not JSON
- Use hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS)
- Progressive enhancement — pages work without JavaScript
- Server renders the UI, HTMX handles the interactivity

## Core Attributes
- `hx-get/post/put/patch/delete` — HTTP methods
- `hx-target` — Where to put the response (CSS selector)
- `hx-swap` — How to swap: `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, `beforeend`, `afterbegin`
- `hx-trigger` — Event that triggers the request
- `hx-indicator` — Loading indicator element

## Best Practices
- DO: Return minimal HTML fragments, not full pages
- DO: Use `hx-boost` on navigation links for SPA-like transitions
- DO: Use `hx-push-url` for browser history management
- DO: Use `hx-confirm` for destructive actions
- DON'T: Build complex client-side state — keep state on the server
- DON'T: Return JSON — return HTML

## Patterns
- Use `hx-swap="outerHTML"` for replacing elements (forms, cards)
- Use `hx-swap="beforeend"` for infinite scroll / append
- Use `hx-trigger="intersect"` for lazy loading
- Use `hx-vals` for sending additional data
- Combine with Alpine.js for client-side micro-interactions
